 \begin{abstract}
 Lattice-based multi-signature schemes still face a fundamental key-management trade-off. PKI-based constructions depend on certificate infrastructures that are costly to deploy and maintain, whereas identity-based alternatives suffer from \emph{key escrow} because the Key Generation Center (KGC) can derive each user's full secret key. Certificateless cryptography resolves this tension by splitting the signing capability between a KGC-issued partial key and a user-generated secret value.
 
-We present \textbf{CL-NTRU-MS-IRS}, a certificateless lattice-based multi-signature scheme over NTRU lattices that, to the best of our knowledge, is the first to incorporate iterative rejection sampling (IRS) in this setting. The revised construction adopts \emph{public-key-bound partial keys}: for each registered public value~$p_i$, the KGC issues a partial key against $\tau_i = H_0(ID_i\|p_i)$, so the effective public key becomes $t_i = H_0(ID_i\|p_i)+p_i$. This registration discipline blocks the direct public-key-replacement forgery that arises in the unbound variant. At the protocol level, the scheme combines (i) a \emph{dual-source key architecture}, in which the effective signing key $\tilde{\bvec{s}}_i = \bvec{d}_i + \bvec{x}_i$ combines a KGC-issued partial key~$\bvec{d}_i$ with a user-chosen secret~$\bvec{x}_i$; (ii) a \emph{two-round commit--reveal protocol} with epoch-scoped validity binding, where the challenge hash includes the signed epoch and a fixed-size digest~$D_{\mathsf{ep}}$ of the published revocation snapshot so that signatures cannot migrate across snapshots; and (iii) \emph{iterative rejection sampling}, which processes non-zero challenge coefficients independently and improves the effective Gaussian ratio from $\alpha = r/\norm{\tilde{\bvec{s}}c}$ to $\alpha = r/\norm{\tilde{\bvec{s}}}$. The $N$ per-signer response vectors are aggregated into a single short vector~$\bvec{z}\in\Ring^2$, while only $N\kappa$ bits of IRS sign-decision metadata are needed for the verifier to reconstruct the per-signer ternary challenge polynomials.
