 \subsection{Security Model}\label{sec:secmodel}
 
 Security in the certificateless setting must be analyzed against two fundamentally different adversary classes~\cite{AlRiyami2003}. A \emph{Type~I adversary} models an external attacker that does not know the master secret but may corrupt users and replace registered public keys. A \emph{Type~II adversary} models a malicious KGC that can generate partial keys for arbitrary identities, yet cannot access users' self-chosen secret values. We formalize both classes below in a registered-key certificateless model with epoch-scoped revocation.
