+\subsection{Prototype arithmetic profile (Set~I micro-benchmark)}\label{sec:runtime_eval}
 
 Following the phase-based methodology commonly used in runtime studies, we report end-to-end runtime by operation phase rather than only asymptotic counts. In our executable prototype we profile five phases: \textsf{Setup}, \textsf{Registration+PartialKey} (for all users), \textsf{SigGen}, \textsf{SigVerify}, and \textsf{SigRevoke}. The arithmetic layer used for these local timings corresponds to the compact Set~I instantiation; a Set~III implementation would work over the larger $(n,q)$ pair and would therefore incur a different raw arithmetic cost while simultaneously removing restart overhead in distributed execution. We sweep the signer count $N \in \{5,10,15,20,25\}$ and repeat each configuration 8 times, reporting the mean and population standard deviation.
 
